Jubilee Party aspirants ordered &lsquo;traitorous&rsquo; independent candidates in Murang&rsquo;a county to leave a hotel where they waited for President Uhuru Kenyatta.They accused them of betraying the party.The independent candidates are among JP primaries losers. The President was supposed to arrive at 9am, but had not arrived by 11am.By that time there was open confrontation.JP members, led by Kiharu MP Irungu Kang&rsquo;ata, demanded Senator Kembi Gitura and other independent candidates leave the Blue Post Hotel near Thika town.&ldquo;We want them to leave the hotel because they were disloyal to the party and are no longer members,&rdquo; Kang&rsquo;ata said.Senator Githura is running for reelection. He lost to Kang&rsquo;ata in the primaries.Transport CS James Macharia was also ejected from the venue for allegedly supporting some independents.Equity Bank chairman Peter Munga was not spared. There has been bad blood between Munga and Governor Mwangi Wairia, who accuses him of sponsoring court cases against his candidacy and funding rival Moses Mwangi.Uhuru and DP William Ruto avoided the debate on independents and instead urged residents to vote for Jubilee.